Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations may occur between chromosomes, not only homologous chromatids. When this occurs, it usually ends up in miscarriage, deformities, and developmental issues.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Endosymbiotic Theory says that mitochondria and chloroplasts were once independent microorganisms that were engulfed by larger microorganisms. However, instead of digesting the mitochondria and then chloroplast for plants, the microorganisms developed a symbiotic relationship in which the larger microorganism provided nutrients for the mitochondria and chloroplast housed inside of its self. In return, the mitochondria allowed the larger microorganism to harvest aerobically formed energy for the first time in history. The chloroplast did the same thing except it creates energy using light from the sun.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The mitochondria is the powerhouse of the cell because it creates a large amount of energy using oxygen. However, if the mitochondria was defective the body would not be able to effectively utilize the oxygen going into it, which could lead to a plethora of problems.
phenomenonA Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonA[comment] Mitochondria are really, really old and passed matrilineally. It has its own unique DNA and by analysing it human migration can be traced all over the world through thousands of years.
phenomenonB Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonB[comment] Translocations between chromosomes may result in a child that can live normally, but it will have reduced fertility due to non homologous chromosomes failing to recombine, meaning fewer viable gametes.
groupTime436 2794.54

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Translocations may occur between chromosomes. This results in a mutant progeny that may or may not exhibit symptoms if it comes to term at all. The offspring may perform mitosis without issue or at reduced efficiency which may result in problems in life. Meiosis will be greatly hindered due to non homologous chromosomes failing to pair. This is what often causes Down's Syndrome.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Endosymbiotic Theory says that chloroplasts and mitochondria were once independent species. They were engulfed by a larger organism, our direct ancestor in the mitochondria case. Instead of eating them, the larger organism joined into a symbiotic relationship with them. Both of the "organelles" are beneficial to the larger cell because together they provide energy more efficiently then anything the world had seen before it. This lead to a massive rise in complexity and paved the way for life to evolve into all of the organisms we see in life, including ourselves.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] The mitochondria's function is to produce energy using oxygen that we breath in through our respiratory system. If the cell can't utilize the oxygen in it, where does it go? Free floating volatile molecules wandering around in a body seems like it could lead to diseases not directly caused by the inefficient mitochondria, but from the waste product's proclivity towards binding with so many different molecules in your body.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Chromosome segments may be inverted in two ways. In paracentric inversion does not involve the centromere. In Pericentric inversion the centromere is included and there is a breakage point on each arm, so the middle segment is changed. If nothing is added or deleted in the process, inversions aren't usually harmful. If additions or deletions occur, the child will have reduced fertility due to the chromosome being nonhomologous with the normal version.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A translocation is a chromosome alteration that results in a whole chromosome or a segment becomes attached to or interchanged with another whole chromosome or segment. There is no gain or loss of genetic material in a translocation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] There are several observations as to why we believe that the mitochondria and chloroplast use to be free living organisms. This relationship was believed to be a mutually beneficial relationship between the cell and these once free living organisms. Some of the evidence that suggests that both the mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events is that both of them have their own cell membranes, mitochondria has its own circular DNA that is passed on to it's offspring and they reproduce in the same process that bacteria do. These are all the major lines of evidence.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Many mitochondrial mutations result in some type of human disease. In petite mitochondrial mutations in yeast causes deficiency in cellular respiration and causes the mitochondria performs abnormal electron transport.
phenomenonA Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonA[comment] Evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events this concept closely relates to endosymbiosis. In endosymbiosis in which a host cell ingested bacteria and then the cell became dependent on each other on order to survive with many years the chloroplast and mitochondria have become specialized in the cell now and can on longer live independently.
phenomenonB Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonB[comment] Translocations can be reciprocal or nonreciprocal. The robertsonian translocation occurs when one chromosome becomes attached to another. A balanced translocation is when no chromosome material was lost or gained during the translocation. The person who carriers this is unaffected by the offspring will be affected because the gametes will have unbalanced translocation.
groupTime436 3081.22

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] In chromosomes there are chromosome abnormalities such as translocations. There are two types of translocation reciprocal and nonreciprocal. In reciprocal translocations two non-homologous chromosomes break and exchange fragments. Individuals with these abnormalities are balanced and usually display normal phenotypes. There is no loss of genetic material in translocation.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] There are several lines of evidence that suggest the ancient symbiotic events of both the mitochondria and chloroplasts. Evidence such as both organelles have their own cell membrane just as most prokaryotes do, they both have their own circular DNA similar to bacterium but slightly smaller and reproduction is similar to that seen in bacteria.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Many mitochondria mutations are associated with impaired mitochondrial function. Respiration can be affected when a mutation occurs. Depending on the mutation the mutation can have a negative or positive affect on the respiration process in mitochondria.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] In chromosomes there are chromosome abnormalities such as inversions. If two breaks occur in one chromosome sometimes the region between them break breaks and rotates 180 degrees before rejoining the two end fragments. Inversions do not cause a gain or loss in genetic material. Therefore, most inversions are viable and usually normal phenotypes observed.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chromosome translocations happen when two non homologous chromosomes rearrange their parts and cause an abnormality. Translocations can be harmless or they can cause genetic disorders. For example, a translocation of the 21st chromosome can cause Downs Syndrome.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Since mitochondria and chloroplasts both have their own separate membranes, this is evidence that they were both symbiotic events. They also both have their own genome so that is further evidence that they were both symbiotic events.

These mutations can be reciprocal in which both chromosomes break off a piece and gain another piece, or nonreciprocal in which only one chromosome breaks off a piece and loses it. However, no DNA is lost in this type of mutation, but it creates havoc in meiosis because of the cross-like pairing formation. Translocations are involved in cancers and even the inherited form of Down syndrome.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The Endosymbiotic Theory states that mitochondria and chloroplasts were once free-living aerobic bacteria that were engulfed by larger anaerobic bacteria to create the eukaryotic cell. As a result, the eukaryotic cell gained the ability to undergo respiration and/or photosynthesis. Evidence for this theory is provided by the 70S ribosomes, small size, and single, circular DNA strand in these organelles.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Mitochondrial mutations can affect respiration because cellular respiration for eukaryotes occurs in the inner membrane of mitochondria; therefore, a mutation can alter the ability to respire. These mutations are inherited from the mother because mitochondria are only passed down from the mother. These mutations can result in diseases like LHON, MERF, Alzheimer's, and heteroplasmy.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Inversion is a type of chromosomal mutation that involves the flipping of a chromosomal segment; however, no DNA material is lost in this mutation. These can be paracentric in which the centromere is not included in the inversion or pericentric in which the centromere is included in the inversion and thus changes the lengths of the chromosome arms. Inversions in drosophila, for example, led to speciation.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A translocation is a a chromosomal mutation associated with the reciprocal or nonreciprocal transfer of a chromosomal segment from one chromosome to another another. When the translocation is reciprocal, genetic material is neither lost nor gained. Other times, genetic material can be lost with abnormal synapsis or Robertsonian translocations, where the arm of one chromosome fuses onto the arm of a nonhomologous chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ002] It is believed that mitochondria and chloroplast arose independently but both possessed skills that the other required. Bacteria were engulfed by larger eukaryotic organisms leading to a symbiotic relationship. The eukaryotic cells gained oxidative respiration and photosynthesis. DNA in chloroplasts and mitochondria look very similar to DNA in bacteria. Chloroplast DNA encodes for many different gene products including distinct ribosomes. Mitochondrial DNA lacks introns.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondrial DNA is extremely vulnerable to mutations. It does not have structural protection from mutations by histone proteins. DNA repair mechanisms in mtDNA are limited. Mitochondria concentrate highly reactive oxygen species, which are toxic to the organelle. Mitochondria carry out respiration so when there is damage to the mtDNA, the mitochondria is unable to mask these mutations which affects respiration.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] A small percentage of Down Syndrome cases occur because of a Robertsonian translocation where one parent has the majority of one chromosome 21 translocated to one end of chromosome 14. The parent could be phenotypically normal and the child would then inherit familial Down syndrome. Other potential offspring could have a standard genome or a balanced translocation.
phenomenonB Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration.
phenomenonB[comment] One disease that arises from mitochondrial mutations is myoclonic epilepsy and ragged-red fiber disease (MERRF). MERRF patients have symptoms of deafness, muscle jerking and weakness and more. It is caused by a mutation in gene for tRNAlys which disrupts the synthesis of mitochondrial proteins needed in electron transport. All of this is a result of the mitochondria being unable to produce ATP normally.
groupTime436 28000.5

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Translocations are the transfer of a chromosomal segment between nonhomologous chromosomes and can be reciprocal or nonreciprocal. Reciprocal translocations can lead to a rearrangement of genetic material where nothing is lost or gained, which would not directly alter the viability of someone who has that. Other times, gametes produced as a result of translocation may be unbalanced. Genetically unbalanced gametes often do not produce viable offspring and may be semisterile. Robertsonian translocations involve breaks at the extreme ends of a short arms of 2 nonhomologous chromosomes and the larger segment fuses to another chromosome creating a metacentric chromosome. Possible gametes for that could be normal, a translocation carrier, a possible trisomy, or a monosomic lethal.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The presence of DNA in mitochondria and chloroplasts in a form that more closely resembles bacterial DNA than eukaryotic DNA and the presence of a genetic system capable of organelle-specific transcription and translocation led to the endosymbiotic theory. This states that mitochondria and chloroplasts as bacteria were engulfed by larger eukaryotic organisms which led to a symbiotic relationship. Chloroplast and mitochondrial DNA both encode numerous gene products and have their own ribosomes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Mitochondria are the organelle that produces ATP via respiration in the cell. When the mitochondria is damaged or has mutations, this will affect the cells respiration. Some eukaryotes, like facultative anaerobes, are able to survive the loss of mitochondrial function by generating energy anaerobically but other times mitochondrial mutations can lead to severe disorders, especially in humans. Mitochondrial DNA is susceptible to mutations because there is no structural protection from histones, repair mechanisms are limited and there is a high concentration reactive oxygen species generated by respiration which is toxic to the mitochondria. Mitochondrial diseases follow a maternal pattern of inheritance.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] One type of chromosome aberration is an inversion. This is when a segment of a chromosome is turned around 180 degrees within the chromosome. There is no loss of genetic information in an inversion it is only rearranged. Inversions can be paracentric and not include the centromere or pericentric, which is when the centromere is part of the inverted segment. Organisms that are heterozygous for inversions may produce aberrant chromosomes that impact their offspring. If crossing over occurs within an inversion loop, abnormal chromosomes are produced. Inversions have the effect of suppressing the recovery of the crossover products when the chromosome exchange occurs within the inverted region.

groupTime435 73.01

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations occur whenever a chromosomal segment moves to a new location in the genome. These movements can occur between chromosomes. In a Robertsonian translocation, the short arms of two nonhomolgous chromosomes break off. The two short segments of the chromosomes are lost but the two long segments join together to make on long chromosome. In reciprocal translocations, two nonhomologous chromosomes exchange segments. The information coded on these segments will still be present in the genome as they have simply been relocated. However, in a Robertsonian translocation, the short segments that break off are lost from the genome. Translocations between nonhomologous chromosomes can cause problems with synapsis in cellular reproduction, while translocation between homologous chromosomes that result in iversions can also cause problems in synapsis.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Both mitochondria and chloroplasts are believed to be ancient symbiotic events. The belief is that both of these organelles were engulfed by larger primitive eukaryotic cells that lacked the ability to respire aerobically or to capture energy from sunlight. As the host cells have evolved, so have the mitochondria in the host cells. The mitochondria have transferred many of their genes to the nucleus of the host cell. Now, the products of the genes are encoded and transcribed in the nucleus before being translated in the cytoplasm prior to their transport to the mitochondria. In addition, the amount of DNA present today in a mitochondria genome is miniscule compared to the free-living bacteria from which it was derived. Similar changes characterize the evolution of chloroplasts.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration because the mitochondria are responsible for generating ATP during aerobic cellular respiration. In fact, mitochondrial DNA are particularly vulnerable to mutations because they have no structural protection from mutations provided by histone proteins present in nuclear DNA, repair mechanisms for mitochondrial DNA are limited, and mitochondria concentrate highly mutagenic reactive oxygen species generated by cell respiration. Since the mitochondria is the organelle responsible for respiration and producing ATP, if the mitochondrial DNA responsible for producing mitochondria is damaged then the mitochondria will not perform its functions correctly and cell respiration will be impacted.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Robertsonian translocations between different chromosomes can produce individuals with Down Syndrome. This occurs when the majority of one of the parents' chromosome 21 is translocated to the end of chromosome 14. This can lead to three copies of chromosome 21 being present in the offspring if the affected parent passes on both a normal chromosome 21 and the chromosome 14 that is attached to the translocated chromosome 21.
phenomenonB Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration.
phenomenonB[comment] Mitochondrial mutations can negatively affect an individual. In myoclonic epilepsy and ragged red-fiber disease (MERRF), mitochondrial mutations are responsible for individuals having ataxia, deafness, dementia,and epileptic seizures.

Then the long segments of the two chromosomes join together to make a long chromosome. I also understand that translocation between chromosomes can occur as a reciprocal translocation when no genetic information is lost but it is transferred from one chromosome to another. In this case, both chromosomes lose some of their genetic material to another chromosome but gain some from that chromosome as well. I understand that this can cause problems during synapsis in cellular reproduction. I also understand that due to translocations, cellular information can be inverted and this can cause problems during synapsis as well.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that at one time mitochondria and chloroplasts existed as entirely self sufficient individuals. groupTime435 39.5

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocation is the rearrangement of parts between two nonhomologous chromosomes. Translocations can result no extra or missing genetic information or an unequal translocation resulting in extra or missing genetic information. A Robertsonian translocation is a type of translocation where the chromosome breaks near the centromere. This results in one large chromosome and one very small chromosome which contains very few genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] It is thought that organelles with two distinct membranes were once separate living organisms which became endosymbionts. This is due to the presence of the original membrane and the membrane created when the organism was phagocytized. The fact that DNA is found in both the nucleus and mitochondria suggests that an organisms consumed another which survived and the relationship eventually became mutualistic.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Since cellular respiration occurs within the mitochondria, mitochondrial DNA mutations may affect respiration. All mitochondria are inherited through the mother's egg. A male with a mitochondrial mutation will not pass down the mutation to his offspring.
phenomenonA Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonA[comment] All organisms live amongst one another. In some extreme cases they can be consumed by larger organisms and eventually become integral to the function of that cell. In the laboratory, it is usually the goal to obtain a pure culture. This is never found in nature and may have some effect on how the organism grows, even when supplemented with all the essential nutrients and conditions it needs to survive. The astonishing idea that a eukaryote swallowed a prokaryote that was capable of aerobic respiration/photosynthesis, and utilized this capability to satisfy one of it's own needs is evidence to the reliance of a cell to live among different organisms in one community.
phenomenonB Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration.
phenomenonB[comment] Evolution is sometimes associated with an increase in complexity. Communities of organisms will sometimes lose nonessential genes which goes against this idea of increased complexity. Mitochondria may have lost some of their early DNA since some metabolic functions were being taken care of by the host, and vice-versa. Some cyanobacteria in the oceans such as Prochlorococcus, have lost the ability to synthesize catalase, an enzyme involved in the breakdown of reactive oxygen species. Smaller "helper" heterotrophs are responsible for the production of catalase. The prototrophs took advantage of this "leaky" system and no longer needed to synthesize the enzyme.
groupTime436 2306.99

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The change in location of a chromosome or portion of a chromosome, is a translocation. No DNA is lost or gained. The chromosome can change position within the same chromosome or transfer to a segment of a nonhomologous chromosome. In nonreciprocal interchromosomal translocations, only one segment is transferred from one chromosome to another. Reciprocal translocation is when two segments are exchanged.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The presence of two membranes, prokaryotic circular DNA, and the location for essential metabolic processes gives evidence to the endosymbiotic theory. Large eukaryotic cells engulfed smaller prokaryotic cells that could either undergo aerobic respiration or photosynthesis. These endosymbionts lost the ability to function on their own over time. This resulted in the eukaryotic cells we see today, containing mitochondria and chloroplasts.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Glycolosis occurs in the cytoplasm until it is converted into pyruvate within the lumen of the mitochondria. It then is inserted into the Krebs cycle where carbon dioxide is produced. If any genetic mutation affects this cycle then respiration will be altered.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Inversions will rearrange the linear sequence of the genes. Pericentric inversions of genes include the centromere while paracentric inversions leave the centromere unaffected. Dicentric bridges and acentric fragments will cause chromosome breakage if crossing over occurs within an inversion loop formed during meiosis.

groupTime435 33.51

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations occur when genetic material is moved to a new location in the genome. Genetic material is not lost or gained; it only changes location in the genome. Translocations can either involve the exchange or transfer of genetic material between two chromosomes. In a nonreciprocal exchange, one chromosome transfers genetic material to another chromosome and does not receive any new material in return. In a reciprocal exchange, the genetic material is swapped between the two chromosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The theory of endosymbiosis suggests that both the mitochondria and the chloroplast were ancient cyanobacteria that were engulfed by a eukaryotic cell. Biologists who support the endosymbiotic theory point to several similarities between the mitochondria/chloroplast and prokaryotic bacteria. They have their own DNA, which is separate from the DNA found in the nucleus of the cell and both organelles use their DNA to produce many proteins and enzymes required for their function. A double membrane surrounds both mitochondria and chloroplasts, suggesting that each was ingested by a primitive host. The two organelles also reproduce like bacteria, replicating their own DNA and directing their own division.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The mitochondrial membrane contains the electron transport chain that is vital for respiration. When mutations occur in mitochondrial DNA, it can affect the gene products that are produced for respiration, in particular for the ETC. Defective or absent gene products due to mutant mitochondrial DNA affect respiration since the ETC is usually deficient of the required proteins.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Translocations contain a smaller subcategory of chromosome aberrations called Robertsonian Translocations. This type of translocation occurs when the long arms of two chromosomes fuse as well as the shorter heterochromatin ends of the chromosomes. This process creates one large chromosome that is made up of the two fused chromosomes. Familial Down Syndrome results when both chromosomes 21 fuse to create one large chromosome 21. The resulting zygotes will have Down syndrome since they have 3 copies of the genes contained in chromosomes 21.
phenomenonB Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration.
phenomenonB[comment] The mitochondria membrane contains the electron transport chain which is vital for respiration. When mutations occur in mitochondrial DNA, it can affect the gene products that are produced for respiration, in particular for the ETC. The result is less ATP produced for the organism. This is why many mitochondrial genetic disorders involve symptoms influenced such as energy deficiency.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations is when a chromosomal segment moves from one chromosome to another. It may either involve one chromosome donating it's segment of another or it may involve both of the chromosome's donating to each other.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The endosymbiotic theory says that mitochondria and chloroplasts arose separately from one another a long time ago. The basis of the theory is that these cells with the chloroplasts and mitochondria where "engulfed" by eukaryotic cells who originally lacked the ability to respirate with oxygen or to use energy from the sun. After they engulfed these bacteria they gained these functions.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration because mitochondrial DNA is highly vulnerable to mutations due to the reactive oxygen species (ROS) generated by cell respiration. Mutations to the ROS can affect cellular respiration.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Translocations or more specifically Robertsonian translocation can lead to familial Down Syndrome. This results in familial Down Syndrome since one parent has a 14/21 D/G translocation which leads to a normal parent but the gametes having a trisomy for 21.
phenomenonB Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonB[comment] I learned about primitive eukaryotic cells engulfing bacteria-like cells with either chloroplasts or mitochondria in my biology class freshman year. This relates to the fact on why plants can use sunlight to produce energy and why cells can respirate aerobically.
groupTime436 1591.7

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that translocation is the movement of a chromosomal segment to a new location in the genome. It can be a reciprocal translocation meaning it involves the exchange of segments between 2 non homologous chromosomes or it can be a non-recipricol translocation meaning it only involves the exchange of segment from one chromosome to another. Translocations can lead to a plethora of effects and involves in rearrangement of genetic material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the endosymbiotic theory explains the origin of eukaryotic cells from prokaryotes. Some of the key organelles of eukaryotes (chloroplasts and mitochondria) originated from protobacteria 2 billion years ago and eventually they were engulfed by primitive eukaryotic cells making the cells we know of today. The primitive eukaryotic cells engulfing these bacteria gave them the function of photosynthesis and aerobic respiration.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that mitochondrial mutations effect respiration because mtDNA gene products include 13 proteins required for aerobic cellular respiration. A cell's energy supply is largely dependent on aerobic cellular respiration to generate ATP and disruption of any mitochondrial gene via mutation can have a severe impact on the organism.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that inversion is a type of chromosomal aberration in which a segment of chromosome is turned around 180 degrees within a chromosome. An inversion doesn't lose genetic information but rearranges the linear gene sequence. A paracentric inversion is when the centromere is not part of the rearranged chromosome segment. A pericentric inversion is when the centromere is apart of the rearranged chromosome segment.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Inversion is another class of structural variation. This is a type of chromosomal aberration in which a segment of a chromosome is turned around 180 degrees within a chromosome. An inversion does not involve a loss of genetic information, but just a rearrangement. There are two types of inversion: paracentric and pericentric. Paracentric does not include the centromere while pericentric does.Even though it appears to have minimal impact on the individuals, geneticists have a great interest in this phenomenon.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations are a type of chromosomal aberration in which a piece of chromosome is moved to a new location in an organism's genome. This type of mutation can occur within or between chromosomes. When translocation occurs between chromosomes, diseases such as Down Syndrome can occur where the translocation results in a trisomic cell.
explainConcepts[SQ002] There is a great deal of scientific research that supports the claim that mitochondria and chloroplasts developed out of ancient symbiotic events. Basically what the evidence shows is that both mitochondria and chloroplasts arose independetly about 2 billion years ago from primitive bacterial cells. These ancient bacterial cells were engulfed by larger primitive eukaryotic cells lacking the abililites to either respire aerobically or capture energy from sunlight. From this engulfment, a symbiotic relationship formed between the primitive bacterial and primitive eukaryotic cell. The bacterial cell lost its ability to live independently and the eukaryotic cell gained the ability to respire aerobically or capture energy from sunlight.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondria are the cell organelle that is primarily responsible for carrying out respiration. When mutations occur to this cell structure, respiration can be significantly impacted. Because the electron transport system is such a specific process, any minor changes made to the ETC or mitochondrial membrane can affect how well the cell carries out oxidation phosphorylation, thereby affecting how much energy the cell is able to produce.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] This concept relates to the biological phenomenon that is Familial Down Syndrome. Familial Down Syndrome is different from the other types of Down Syndrome in that it results from a translocation of part of chromosome 21 to chromosome 14. A parent with this type of translocation is phenotypically normal and is considered a balanced translocation carrier. This individual however can produce gametes that contain two copies of chromosome 21. Upon fertilization, these gametes will now contain 3 copies of the chromosome 21 resulting in a Down Syndrome child.
phenomenonB Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonB[comment] This topic refers to the important biological phenomenon in which mitochondria and chloroplasts were developed. Billions of years ago when a primitive eukaryotic cell engulfed a primitive bacterial cell capable of aerobic respiration or capturing energy from sunlight, the bacterial cell continued living inside the bigger eukaryotic cell and eventually developed into mitochondria and chloroplasts. With out this event, life as we know it today would not exist.

Inversion heterozygotes can be paired only if they form an inversion loop. If crossing over occurs in the inversion loop then abnormal chromatids are produced.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Sometimes segments are moved from one chromosome to another non-homologous chromosome. These events are called translocations, and they usually have powerful effects on the organisms that they produce (assuming the translocation occurs in a gamete).
explainConcepts[SQ002] The prokaryotic nature of mitochondrial and chloroplast DNA indicates that at one point, eukaryotic cells may have absorbed prokaryotes that served similar purposes as the modern day mitochondria and chloroplasts. The eukaryotes and prokaryotes formed a symbiotic relationship, and the prokaryotes gradually became a part of the eukaryotes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that translocations are like crossing-over events, except they occur between non-homologous chromosomes. Because of this uneven exchange of genetic material, the effects of the translocation are usually negative and often lethal. I understand that translocations can be reciprocal, meaning that segments are exchanged between two chromosomes, or non-reciprocal, meaning that one segment is simply transferred to another chromosome. I also understand that there is a special type of reciprocal translocation called Robertsonian translocation, wherein one large hybrid chromosome and one small chromosomal fragment are formed. The fragment is normally discarded during meiosis.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that the prokaryotic nature of mitochondrial and chloroplast DNA indicates that at one point, eukaryotic cells may have absorbed prokaryotes that served similar purposes as the modern day mitochondria and chloroplasts. I understand that evidence suggests that the eukaryotes and prokaryotes formed a symbiotic relationship, and the prokaryotes gradually became a part of the eukaryotes. This co-evolution resulted in the structures that we see in all animals and chlorophyll-containing plants that we see today.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that because the mitochondria are the site at which cellular respiration occurs, mutations in mitochondrial DNA can have a direct effect on an organisms respiratory ability. Any changes in the genes that produce proteins directly involved in the Krebs cycle or any other aspect of the process of cellular respiration can impair an organism's ability to carry out these life-sustaining processes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that the linear sequence of alleles on a chromosome can become reversed during DNA-replication or through cross over events. This means that a chromosome with the alleles ABCD could be inverted into ACBD. I understand that these inversions may have catastrophic consequences for the organism, or they may have virtually no effect--it simply depends on where the alteration is and exactly how the genes have been moved. I understand that inversions can cause the chromosomes to pair in odd ways during mitosis and meisos. Normally, the inverted chromosome forms a loop, so that the corresponding genes can maintain physical contact.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations occur when one portion of a chromosome is moved as a chunk in its entirety. It does not lose or gain any genetic information, but the position of the genes are moved. A reciprocal translocation occurs when one part of a chromosome is exchanged with another, and a nonreciprocal translocations occurs when one part of a chromosome is moved from one chromosome to another without any exchange.
explainConcepts[SQ002] There are differences between the DNA of mitochondria and chloroplasts when compared to the DNA of the cell of interest. This DNA is entirely different, and it is thought that chloroplasts and mitochondria came to be in plant and animal cells respectively through these organelles entering the cell and forming a symbiotic relationship. This endosymbiosis theory explains the differences in the DNA between these organelles and the host cell.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The mitochondria is home to respiration. Mutations in these organelles can result in the organelles not working at optimum function or not working at all. For example, a mutation that minimizes the mitochondria's amount of ATP synthase would result in not creating enough energy in the form of ATP. A non-functioning organelle that is pivotal for respiration would ultimately result in cell death.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Translocation of the 21st chromosome can result in familial Down Syndrome and can increase the probability of offspring in future generations having Down Syndrome.
phenomenonB Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonB[comment] Roberstonian translocations occur when two chromosomes are separated and translocated and result in one chromosome with two large sections and another chromosome with two small sections. The smaller section is usually lost afterwards.

explainConcepts[SQ001] A translocation is a change in location of a DNA segment. This is a chromosome abnormality and can occur between two chromosomes. It can be a balanced transfer, unbalanced, reciprocal, or Robertsonian--which results in a karyotype of less than 46 and a metacentric chromosome where the the location of the chromosome segment has been moved to.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Mitochondria and chrloroplasts have DNA quite similar to that of bacteria, which has caused scientists to theorize that these organelles began as primitive bacteria a couple million years ago. The Endosymbiotic Theory theorizes that these primitive bacteria were engulfed by eukaryotic cells which gave the host cells the abilities of cellular respiration and photosynthesis.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondrial gene products account for the 13 proteins crucial for aerobic cellular respiration and the production of ATP. If a mutation--which is a change in the DNA sequence--occurs in one of the protein sequences, a varying degree of affects can be attributed to the mutation, ranging from slight to severe or even lethal.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Robertsonian translocations have been found to be another genetic source of Down syndrome. Particularly, familial Down syndrome occurs with a translocation between chromosome 14 and chromosome 21. Knowledge of Robertsonian translocations and the karyotype would allow for knowledge of the probability of affected progeny.
phenomenonB Translocations may occur between chromosomes.

explainConcepts[SQ001] A translocation is a type of chromosomal mutation in which pieces of a chromosome rearrange onto another nonhomologous chromosome. A reciprocal translocation is when the chromosomes trade pieces. A nonreciprocal translocation is a piece moves to another chromosome, but no piece is exchanged. Robertsonian translocations are a type of translocation in which a break occurs at or near the centromeres of two acrocentric chromosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] This is called endosymbiosis. A host prokaryotic cell engulfed a smaller eukaryotic cell and used its metabolic processes for its own use. Evidence includes similarities in the genome found in chloroplasts and mitochondria to eukaryotic cells.
explainConcepts[SQ003] The synthesis of ATP, the cell's energy currency, depends on processes that occur in the mitochondrial membrane. When the structure of mitochondria are changed due to mutations, the function also changes, and respiration is affected.

groupTime435 36.38

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] A change in location of a chromosome segment is a translocation, but during the change no DNA is lost or gained. Simple translocations are of two types: intrachromosomal (a change of position within the same chromosome) and interchromosomal (a transfer of the segment to a non homologous chromosome) If a segment is transferred from one chromosome to another, it is nonreciprocal. If segments are exchanged, it is reciprocal.
explainConcepts[SQ002] New mitochondria and plastids are formed only through a process similar to binary fission. If a cell's mitochondria or chloroplasts are removed, they do not have the means to create new ones. Genome comparisons indicate that cyanobacteria contributed to the genetic origin of plastids. DNA sequence analysis and phylogenetic estimates suggest that nuclear DNA contains genes that probably came from plastids. These organelles' ribosomes are like those found in bacteria. Much of the internal structure and biochemistry of plastids, for instance the presence of thylakoids and particular chlorophylls, is very similar to that of cyanobacteria. Mitochondria have several enzymes and transport systems similar to those of bacteria. Both mitochondria and plastids have small genomes compared to bacteria. This is consistent with an increased dependence on the eukaryotic host after forming an endosymbiosis. Most genes on the organellar genomes have been lost or moved to the nucleus. Most genes needed for mitochondrial and plastid function are located in the nucleus. Many originate from the bacterial endosymbiont.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondrial disease is a group of disorders caused by dysfunctional mitochondria, the organelles that generate energy for the cell. Mitochondrial diseases are sometimes (about 15% of the time)[1] caused by mutations in the mitochondrial DNA that affect mitochondrial function. Other causes of mitochondrial disease are mutations in genes of the nuclear DNA, whose gene products are imported into the mitochondria (mitochondrial proteins) as well as acquired mitochondrial conditions.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Chromosomal translocations can play a role in diseases such as cancer, Down Syndrome, sexually-inherited diseases/conditions (Kleinfelt Syndrome). I personally am interested in if there is a cure at the genetic level to correct the chromosome mutation and/or lessen the chance for these mutations in their progeny.
phenomenonB Mitochondrial mutations affect respiration.
phenomenonB[comment] Mitochondrial diseases range from Mitochondrial myopathy; Diabetes mellitus and deafness (DAD); Leber's hereditary optic neuropathy (LHON); Leigh syndrome, subacute sclerosing encephalopathy; Neuropathy, ataxia, retinitis pigmentosa, and ptosis (NARP); Myoneurogenic gastrointestinal encephalopathy (MNGIE); Mitochondrial myopathy, encephalomyopathy, lactic acidosis, stroke-like symptoms (MELAS); and others, and can be caused by mutations, acquired or inherited, in mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) or in nuclear genes that code for mitochondrial components. Although research is ongoing, treatment options are currently limited; vitamins are frequently prescribed, though the evidence for their effectiveness is limited. Membrane penetrating antioxidants have the most important role in improving mitochondrial dysfunction. Pyruvate has been proposed recently as a treatment option. Spindle transfer, where the nuclear DNA is transferred to another healthy egg cell leaving the defective mitochondrial DNA behind, is a potential treatment procedure that has been successfully carried out on monkeys. Using a similar pronuclear transfer technique, researchers at Newcastle University successfully transplanted healthy DNA in human eggs from women with mitochondrial disease into the eggs of women donors who were unaffected. In June 2013, the United Kingdom government agreed to develop legislation that would legalize the 'three-person IVF' procedure as a treatment to fix or eliminate mitochondrial diseases that are passed on from mother to child. The procedure could be offered from 29 October 2015 once regulations had been established.

groupTime435 37.1

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations are the breaking off and the transfer of a portion of a chromosome to another chromosome. This transfer can be discussed as a reciprocal translocation between nonhomologous chromosomes or as a non-reciprocal translocation of nonhomologous chromosomes. In a reciprocal translocations, two chromosomes that are not homologous chromosomes to each other both actively switch portions of their individual chromosome, thus, creating a hybrid-like chromosome. In this, both chromosomes act like a receiver and a donor for a piece of that chromosome. However, in a non-reciprocal translocation of nonhomologous chromosomes, only one chromosome acts like the receiver and one acts like the donor. Non-reciprocal translocations consist of the transfer of hereditary material from only one chromosome to be attached to another nonhomologous chromosome. Another way to describe the rearrangement of chromosomes is known as Robertsonian Translocation which is the transfer of a portion of a chromosome amongst these chromosomal numbers only 13, 14, 15, 21, and 22.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Endosymbiotic Theory is a theory that explains the origination of mitochondria and chloroplast within the current eukaryotic cell. This theory claims that the mitochondria and the chloroplast were previously prokaryotic organisms, proteobacteria and cyanobacteria, respectively, that coexisted with the now eukaryotic bacteria in a symbiotic relationship. There are numerous evidences that show or support this possible explanation. For instance, both the chloroplast and the mitochondria have their own DNA and have their own replication mechanisms separate from the nucleus. The former prokaryotic organelles have DNA, ribosomes, and transport enzymes like that of bacteria. Furthermore, there are other lines of evidence that suggest this symbiosis between the chloroplast and the mitochondria to the eukaryotic cell and the actual process of the symbioitc event. However, in class I was informed that some facts were overlooked that disagreed with the concept of the endosymbiotic theory due to the fact that individuals wanted every detail to match the idea that was created.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mitochondria are responsible for producing ATP within the cell to be utilized by the mitochondrial cell and the eukaryotic cell while some energy is wasted in the form of heat. This production of ATP is crucial to allow certain functions to occur within an organism. Furthermore in order to produce this energy, mitochondria must utilize oxygen along with other molecules to initiate the process of aerobic respiration. Therefore, any mutation that results in the reduction of mitochondrias within a cell or inhibits the production of ATP through interference during the exothermic process can result in respiratory diseases. A lower number of mitochondrias directly respond to a lower and limited oxygen absorption or intake and ATP production, thus affecting respiration.
phenomenonA Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonA[comment] I have always found the endosymbiotic theory very intriguing. I do know that this theory was initially rejected as it defied many principles that were believed or assumed in the early 1800-1900s. Furthermore, I do know that mitochondria remarkably resemble alpha proteobacteria due to similarities in the DNA, ribosomal characteristics, and the ability to undergo binary fission. However, chloroplasts entering and coexisting in an eukaryotic cell were a part of the secondary endosymbiosis and resemble Cyanobacteria which are photosynthetic bacteria . I am interested in finding out what evidence defies or could potentially disprove the endosymbiotic theory.
phenomenonB Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonB[comment] I do know that translocations are a type of chromosomal aberration that result in the transfer of a portion of the chromosome onto another nonhomologous chromosome. I have described earlier what occurs in a translocation, but I am interested in finding out how this mutation occurs especially since the individuals with translocations are usually phenotypically normal since all the genes are still present. I am interested in what causes this transfer of chromosomal pieces and learning about certain disorders resulting from translocations.

Furthermore, Robertsonian translocations are translocations that are noted and involve the transfer of chromosomal information between the following chromosomes: 13, 14, 15, 21, and 22. In addition, the only type of heredity Down's Syndrome, Familial Down's, is caused by a translocation in which a portion of chromosome 21 is attached to chromosome 14. knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand this topic really well, but I do not know what facts or evidences are present that could reject or disprove certain portions of the endosymbiotic theory. The endosymbiotic theory describes that mitochondria and chloroplasts both were initially prokaryotic bacteria that were engulfed by another organism and led a symbiotic relationship in which the mitochondria (former alpha proteobacteria) gave the eukaryotic cell more ATP and enabled aerobic respiration while the chloroplast provided means of producing its own sugar from many metabolic conversions from light energy of the Sun, while the eukaryotic cell provided protection. This theory also showed similarities between the mitochondria and chloroplast ( former Cyanobacteria) to bacterial cells through various ways. knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Inversions are the result of a sequence of DNA on a chromosome becoming inverted or flipped. There are two types of inversions, paracentric which do not involve the centromere of a chromosome and pericentric inversions which do involve the centromere. Pericentric inversions can results in a chromosome becoming acentric (no centromere) and dicentric (two centromeres); paracentric inversions commonly create a inversion loop of the individual is heterozygous for that inversion. Furthermore, inversions do complicate the process of meiosis especially during separation thus needing a different configuration to enable an easier separation. I am curious if an individual can have a DNA sequence on a chromosome that is both translocated and inverted.

DNA Each mitochondrion & chlorolplast has its own circular DNA genome, like a bacteria's genome, but much smaller. This DNA is passed from a mitochondrion to its offspring and is separate from the "host" cell's genome in the nucleus. bacteria/mitochondria structural comparison Reproduction Mitochondria multiply by pinching in half the same process used by bacteria. knowlegeBasis[SQ004] If two breaks occur in one chromosome, sometimes the region between the breaks rotates 180 degrees before rejoining with the two end fragments. Such an event creates a chromosomal mutation called an inversion. Unlike deletions and duplications, inversions do not change the overall amount of the genetic material, so inversions are generally viable and show no particular abnormalities at the phenotypic level. In some cases, one of the chromosome breaks is within a gene of essential function, and then that breakpoint acts as a lethal gene mutation linked to the inversion.

knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Inversion results in part of the chromosome getting reversed. If this happens the bases on the chromosome can be altered resulting in a alternate protein formation. The two types of inversions include paricentric inversion (includes centromere) and paracentric inversions (excludes centromere). Meiotic pairing of heterozygotes for a paracentric inversion can result in crossing over within the loop of the inversion of the chromosome and can cause chromosome breakage.

explainConcepts[SQ002] Evolutionists are trying to link the idea that mitochondria used to be separate organisms which eventually started living inside eukaryotesto provide energy. explainConcepts[SQ003] Because the DNA repair mechanism in mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) is limited, the energy-producing capability of mitochondria is limited when mutations occur in the mtDNA.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.

This means that the carrier of the translocation can have a child with the genetic material for 3 chromosome 21s. This is a rare cause of Down syndrome.
phenomenonB Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonB[comment] A condition known as semisterility occurs when fewer than 50% of the progeny of an individual heterozygous for a reciprocal translocation survive. This is because of the genetically unbalanced gametes produced by such an individual.

groupTime435 634.91

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Translocations of genetic material between chromosomes can result in a variety of effects. When the translocation occurs in a specific individual, that individual is usually phenotypically normal because they still have the correct amount of genetic material, just in different places. However, if influences such as position effect alter or disrupt the expression of the translocated genes, then the individual will not be phenotypically normal. The progeny of individuals with translocations, on the other hand, will not be normal if they inherit one of the translocated chromosomes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In learning about the way that both mitochondria and chloroplasts function in the cell, they stand out as distinct from the other organelles in that they have their own machinery and DNA replication systems. In researching further the mechanisms of these organelles, they appear to have striking similarities to independent, prokaryotic organisms. These lines of research have implicated that the origin and incorporation of these organelles into living systems today are a result of an ancient symbiotic relationship between two separate prokaryotic cells.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Mutations in mitochondrial DNA have led to a variety of impacts on respiration in cells. While over time through evolution, these mutations have led to the incorporation of a prokaryotic bacterium into the host cell, there are also respiratory syndromes that result from deleterious mutations. One such syndrome is Leigh syndrome, which is a severe neurological disorder resulting from mutations in mitochondrial DNA. Since mitochondria have their own DNA, mutations in these genes affect the gene products and functioning of the mitochondria itself. Because the mitochondria is involved in respiration and many events associated with respiration occur in the mitochondria, these mutated or absent gene products directly affect respiration.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] One example of translocation between chromosomes is seen in familial Down syndrome. The translocation occurs between the D and G groups of chromosomes, most notably between chromosome 21 and 14. This is personally relevant because Ive spent a lot of time working with special needs children with Down syndrome, and it is interesting to learn about the potential mechanisms of the syndrome.
phenomenonB Several lines of evidence suggest that both mitochondria and chloroplasts are ancient symbiotic events.
phenomenonB[comment] I think this topic is particularly interesting because it gives significant evidence of evolution. Many times, in the debate or discussion of evolution, there are so many unknowns or assumptions that must be made that there are a variety of theories that can be supported. However, the unique case of mitochondria and chloroplasts operating in such a way that it appears they were actually separate organisms that originally just had a symbiotic relationship with its host (exchanging valuable nutrients with available energy sources). Learning about topics such as this is interesting because it spans two very distinct fieldsgenetics and history.
groupTime436 2076.7

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that translocations occur when genetic material is moved (relocated) to a different chromosome. I understand that these translocations can be either reciprocal or non-reciprocal. In reciprocal translocations, segments of the chromosomes involved are exchanged both ways. In reciprocal translocations, both of the individual chromosomes involved have both lost some genetic material and gained some genetic material. In non-reciprocal translocations, the relocation of genetic material is unidirectional, resulting in one chromosome with missing genetic material and the other with extra genetic material. I also understand the implications of changes in genetic material, and that in an specific individual with a translocation, they can still be phenotypically normal because they still have all the genetic material they need to function, just in different places now. The biggest effects of translocations is seen in the offspring of individuals with translocation, as relocated genetic material can result in unbalanced segregation of genetic information in gametes, which can result in offspring without the normal amount of genetic material.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that research into the mechanisms and functioning of both mitochondria and chloroplasts has led geneticists to believe that the origin of these organelles was a symbiotic relationship between a eukaryotic host cell and a prokaryotic cell. Some of the evidence for this theory is that mitochondria have their own, separate DNA that is distinct from the DNA in the nucleus of the cell. Another piece of evidence is the way mitochondria replicate. Mitochondria replicate via the same mechanism as bacteria, that is, they pinch off from the parent through binary fission. Lastly, mitochondria must come from another parent mitochondria, and the cell cant make itself a new mitochondria if it loses its original one, because it doesnt have the genetic material or machinery.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that mitochondrial mutations have a direct affect on respiration in the cell. The mitochondria is responsible for producing the energy used by the cell, in the from of ATP. When there are deleterious mutations in the mitochondrial DNA, the normal process of respiration in the cell is disrupted, weakened, or worst case, is shut down completely. Aerobic cells need to be able to perform the functions related with respiration through the mitochondria in order to get the energy it needs to function properly.I also understand that advantageous mutations that result in even higher or more efficient respiration are what may have led to the incorporation of the ancient prokaryotic bacteria into the cell as the mitochondria.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that similar to translocations, inversions in individuals have a variety of outcomes, one of which being that an individual is still phenotypically normal despite the inversion. Inversions occur when segments of chromosomal DNA break, then reform connect to the rest of the chromosome in a backwards mannerthat is, they are inverted. Inversion do not result in a lost of genetic material in an individual, but because of how genes are regulated via mechanism such as promoter sequences, inversions also have the ability to shut off genes or prevent genes from being turned on in the normal way. In these cases, inversions lead to a loss or lessening of gene products, but the individual still has the non-inverted homolog that may be sufficient in producing the needed gene products. When an individual with an inversion passes its inverted copy of the chromosome to progeny, the offspring will still inherit the proper amount of genetic material, but again, depending on gene regulation specific to the genes in question, there are a variety of phenotypic results.

quantUnderstanding[SQ002] 4.5
quantUnderstanding[SQ003] 4.5
quantUnderstanding[SQ004] 5 -- Deep understanding: Could interpret and predict behavior of system in novel contexts

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In genetics, a chromosome translocation is a chromosome abnormality caused by rearrangement of parts between nonhomologous chromosomes. A gene fusion may be created when the translocation joins two otherwise-separated genes, it is detected on cytogenetics or a karyotype of affected cells.
explainConcepts[SQ002] DNA in mitochondria and chloroplasts accounts for certain phenotypes in offspring. THe transfer of genetic material is through the cytoplasm and not through information held in the nucleus. THey are both inhereited through maternal cytoplasm. They both contain specific DNA patterns that contribute to their functions.
explainConcepts[SQ003] A cell's energy is dependent on the mitochondria. In humans, we respire aneorobically. Reactive oxygen species are generated by cell respiration and are toxic to the contents of the organelle. they damage proteins, lipids, and mtDNA.
phenomenonA Translocations may occur between chromosomes.
phenomenonA[comment] Reciprocal translocations are usually an exchange of material between nonhomologous chromosomes. Estimates of incidence range from about 1 in 500 to 1 in 625 human newborns.Such translocations are usually harmless and may be found through prenatal diagnosis.
